very decent accommodations at Bettus, and might with comfort take up my abode there for an evening. As I travelled, I re|flected on Burnet's De&s;cription of a part of Carnarvon&s;hire, that it was <Q REND="inline">"the fragment of a de|moli&s;hed world,"</Q> and on making &s;ome &s;light ob&s;ervation to the Guide of the drearine&s;s that &s;ur|rounded me, <Q REND="inline">"Aye, ma&s;ter, &s;ays he, this mu&s;t have been an an|cient country indeed, for you &s;ee it is worn out to the
